The paper deals with real-time pose estimation of spacecraft or object in space, which is a key capability necessary for on-orbit spacecraft servicing and assembly tasks. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Robotics (cs.RO) sub-category. The paper leverages a convolutional neural network to determine the translation and rotation of an object of interest relative to the camera, which suggests that it is likely to belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category. The paper also uses a simulation framework designed for assembly tasks to generate dataset for training the modified CNN models, which suggests that it is likely to belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The paper compares the results of different models with a measure of how accurately models are predicting the pose, which suggests that it is likely to belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with on-orbit spacecraft servicing and assembly tasks, which suggests that it is likely to belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category.
